QUESTION: How do you measure ROI (Return on Investment) of Test Automation?

VERSION 1: BUSINESS / MANAGEMENT / STRATEGIC ANSWER
I measure ROI of automation by comparing the cost of building and maintaining automation versus the business value it delivers.
First, I look at cost factors:
    Initial framework and test development effort
    Ongoing maintenance cost
    Infrastructure and execution cost in CI/CD

Then I look at value factors:
     Reduction in manual regression effort
     Reduction in release cycle time
     Faster feedback to developers
     Reduction in production defects
     Improved release confidence

In practical terms, I track metrics like:
      Manual test execution hours saved per release
      Number of releases supported per month after automation
     Time taken for regression before and after automation
       Defects found in early stages vs production

Stability and reliability of automation suite

If automation allows us to run regression in hours instead of days, support more releases, and catch more defects 
before production, the ROI is clearly positive even if initial investment was high.

Closing line:
For me, ROI is not just cost saving, it is also about speed, risk reduction, and business confidence.

VERSION 2: ENGINEERING / METRICS-DRIVEN / PRACTICAL ANSWER

I measure ROI of automation using very concrete and trackable metrics.
On the cost side, I track:
Effort spent on writing tests
Effort spent on maintaining tests
Execution and infrastructure cost

On the benefit side, I track:
Reduction in manual testing effort
Reduction in regression execution time
Increase in release frequency
Defects caught before production

Pipeline feedback time improvement
Some very practical examples of metrics I use:
    Regression time reduced from 3 days to 3 hours
    Manual testing effort reduced by X person-days per release
    Production defects reduced by X percent

Number of releases increased per month without increasing QA headcount

If automation is saving more engineering and business time than it costs to maintain, and at the same time improving quality 
and delivery speed, then it is giving positive ROI.

Closing line:
Good automation is not an expense, it is a business accelerator.



